Conversions and interop.

Any Scala collection can be converted to any other compatible shape with the to method, naming the target. To-list, to-vector, to-set, to-map — though to-map requires the elements to already be tuples, since a map is built from key-value pairs. Converting a list with a duplicate to a set drops the duplicate, converting to a vector or an array changes the underlying structure, and so on. The older named shortcuts still exist alongside the general form.

For java interop, you cross the boundary explicitly. You import the scala j-d-k collection converters, and then call as-java to hand a Scala collection to java code, or as-scala to wrap a java collection coming back. Notebook one mentioned this seam; here it is in practice. The important point is that the conversion is explicit and visible — a java list is not silently a Scala list, and you mark the crossing with as-java or as-scala so the boundary is never a surprise.

That closes the operations half. With the shapes from part one and these uniform operations, you have the whole everyday Scala collections toolkit — and the two habits to carry forward are derive rather than mutate, and reach for the right shape for your access pattern.
